# More Debugging Tactics

Building on the foundation from "Basic debugging tactics," you now have tools to handle more complex scenarios. The strategies here target situations where simple print statements or stepping through code is not enough.

## Conditional Breakpoints

Rather than pausing at every line, set breakpoints that trigger only when specific conditions are true. In your debugger (GDB, LLDB, or IDE), you can attach conditions like `x == 500` or `result < 0`. This saves time when debugging -- you jump straight to the problematic case instead of manually resuming repeatedly.

## Watchpoints and Memory Inspection

When a variable changes unexpectedly, watchpoints catch the exact moment it happens. Set a watchpoint on a variable, and execution pauses when anything modifies it. This is invaluable for tracking down silent data corruption.

## Logging with Purpose

Strategic logging beats brute-force print statements. Rather than printing everything, target the specific values you need to verify:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int computeDiscount(int price, int discountPercent)
{
    std::cout << "[debug] price=" << price
              << ", discountPercent=" << discountPercent << '\n';

    int discount = price * discountPercent / 100;
    std::cout << "[debug] computed discount=" << discount << '\n';

    int finalPrice = price - discount;
    std::cout << "[debug] finalPrice=" << finalPrice << '\n';

    return finalPrice;
}
```

Log state transitions, boundary conditions, and assumption violations. Structure logs so you can search for patterns.

## Assertions for Invariants

Assertions document what *must* be true. They catch logic errors early:

```cpp
#include <cassert>

int safeDivide(int numerator, int denominator)
{
    assert(denominator != 0);  // This must always hold
    return numerator / denominator;
}
```

In release builds, assertions typically vanish, so use them for development guarantees, not runtime validation.

## Minimal Reproducers

When faced with complex bugs, isolate the smallest program that exhibits the problem. Remove unrelated code, simplify values, hardcode inputs. A short reproducer is worth a thousand lines of context. This forces you to understand what triggers the bug rather than searching blindly through complexity.

## Using the Right Tools

Some bugs need specialized tools: AddressSanitizer catches memory errors, and compiler warnings (enable `-Wall -Wextra`) catch many issues before runtime. Invest time in your toolchain -- it pays dividends.
